The thermophilic and hardy plant 

Isatis indigotica
Fortune (Brassicaceae)

, was widely distributed and cultivated worldwide (

; 

; 

). The dried leaves (Da-Qing-Ye) and roots (Ban-Lan-Gen) of 

I. indigotica

are included in Pharmacopoeia of the People’ s 
Republic of China
(2020), respectively (

; 

). 

I. indigotica

is a famous heat-clearing and detoxifying medicine, which has been commonly applied for treating pestilence and influenza since the Han Dynasty (

; 

). Recent pharmacological investigations indicated that this plant has broad application value in combating pandemic diseases, such as COVID-19, SARS, and H1N1 (

; 

; 

; 

). 

I. indigotica

is a considerable pharmaceutical raw material for its excellent medical value. About 40 patent medicines contained 

I. indigotica

as essential ingredients in the Chinese market, such as Da-Qing-Ye injection and Ban-Lan-Gen granules, and over 1000 pharmaceutical patents containing 

I. indigotica

were authorized until 2022 (

; 

; 

).

Previous phytochemistry research on
I. indigotica
indicated this plant could produce lignans, alkaloids, and flavonoids (
;
). Lignans, one of the most critical chemical ingredients from
I. indigotica
, possess various biological activities, i.e., neuroprotective, enzyme inhibition, and anti-AD activities (
;
;
). In order to seek bioactive lignans, nine tetrahydrofuran lignans including three undescribed ones ( 1a / 1b and 2 ) and two known analogues ( 3a / 3b ), along with four known bistetrahydrofuran lignans ( 4–7 ) were isolated from
I. indigotica .
Compounds 1a / 1b–3a/3b have a novel spiro[dienone-tetrahydrofuran] molecular core. Herein, the isolation, chiral resolution, structure analysis, as well as AChE inhibitory and neuroprotective activities were described.

The relative configurations of 1 can be deduced from the obvious NOE correlations and coupling constant. The NOE correlation of H-7’/H-8 suggested that these protons were placed on the same face of the tetrahydrofuran ring. H-7 was placed on the opposite orientation with H-8 for the cross-peak of H-7/H- 9 in the NOESY experiment. In addition, this assumption has been demonstrated by the large coupling constant of J H-7, H-8 = 9.5 Hz (
;
;
). However, the relative configuration of C-8 ′ could not be determined by the lack of NOE correlation.

Interestingly, compound 
2
is an optically pure compound according to its distinct specific rotation and obvious CD Cotton effect. A single chromatographic peak was eluted by multiple chiral HPLC columns in both the normal and reversion phase, which also provide evidence for its optical purity (

; 

). This phenomenon could be contributed by diverse enzyme commands during the biosynthetic paths (

). According to the calculated ECD curve (
Fig. 5
), the absolute configuration of 
2
was assigned.

Two known spiro[dienone-tetrahydrofuran] lignan enantiomers ( 3a and 3b ) were also obtained and defined as (+)-(7 S ,8 R ,1 ′ S ,7 ′ S ,8 ′ R )- sibiricumin A and ()-(7 R ,8 S ,1 ′ R ,7 ′ R ,8 ′ S )-sibiricumin A (
), respectively. Additionally, compounds 4–7 were identified as acanthoside B (
), eucommin A (
), pinoresinol 4- O -β -D-glucoside (
), and lirioresinol A (
).

As a crucial public health problem, Alzheimer’ s disease (AD) occurrence significantly rises with age (

; 

). The exact etiology and pathogenesis of AD remain unclear, but increased oxidative stress and decreased acetylcholine (ACh) were believed to be critical factors in the development of AD (

; 

; 

; 

). The neuroprotective effects of all tetrahydrofuran lignans were tested, and compounds 
1a
/ 
1b -3a
/ 
3b
showed comparable neuroprotective effects 
in vitro
as Trolox (
Fig. 6
).

Conformational searches for compounds were conducted with MMFF94 force field by SPARTAN software (

; 

). The theoretical ECD calculations were performed by B3LYP/6–311++ G(2d,p)//B3LYP/6-31G(d) on the Gaussian 09 program package (

). The calculated ECD curve was generated using the SpecDis 1.51 software (

; 

).

The NMR shielding constants of compounds 
1
and 
2
were calculated with the gauge-including atomic orbital (GIAO) method based on the procedure described in a previous report (

). The linear correlation coefficient (
R
2
) (

), DP4+ probability (

) and the 
MAEΔΔδ
parameter (

; 

) were calculated to evaluate deviations between the experimental and calculated results.

The H 2 O 2 -induced SH-SY5Y cells model was selected for evaluating the neuroprotective activity of these compounds. SH-SY5Y cells were pretreated with various concentrations (12.5, 25 and 50 μM) of tested samples for 1 h before H 2 O 2 (200 μM) treatment for another 4 h. Then, 20 μL MTT was added to each well at 37 ◦ C for 4 h, and the resultant crystals were dissolved in DMSO. The absorbance was measured at 490 nm . Cell viability was expressed as a percentage relative to the value of the control group (
;
).

The inhibitory assay was operated following the reported description. Compounds 
1–7
were dissolved in DMSO. The mixture contained 50 μL phosphate buffer (pH 7.5), 25 μL of compound at 12.5, 25 and 50 μM, 125 μL of DTNB (0.5 mM) and 12.5 μL AChE (0.1 U/mL), and refrigerated the mixture overnight. The reaction was initiated by the addition of 50 μL of ACTI (0.15 mM). The hydrolysis of ATCI was monitored at 
412 nm
after 5 min. Donepezil was used as positive control (

; 

; 

).

The crystal structures of AChE (PDB ID: 1EVE) with 2.50 Å resolution were selected as the receptor. The lowest energy conformation of 1b was established by Spartan with an MMFF94 force field. Schrodinger Maestro program performed the molecular docking between AChE and 1b , and the results could be visualized by PyMOL (
;
).
